Note: Runa Scientific Computing Module
Note: Superior to NumPy/SciPy with natural language syntax, type safety, and integrated ecosystem
Note: Advanced linear algebra, signal processing, optimization, and scientific algorithms

Import "math/core" as math
Import "collections/list" as list_ops
Import "collections/dict" as dict_ops

Note: =============================================================================
Note: ADVANCED ARRAY OPERATIONS - N-Dimensional Arrays with NumPy-level Performance
Note: =============================================================================

Type called "NDArray":
    data as List[Any]
    shape as List[Integer]
    dtype as String
    ndim as Integer
    size as Integer
    strides as List[Integer]

Type called "ArrayResult":
    success as Boolean
    array as Optional[NDArray]
    error_message as Optional[String]

Process called "create_ndarray" that takes 
    data as List[Any]
    and shape as Optional[List[Integer]]
    and dtype as Optional[String]
    returns ArrayResult:

    Note: Create N-dimensional array with specified shape and data type
    Try:
        Let array_dtype be dtype or "float64"
        Let flat_data be flatten_nested_list with list as data
        
        Let inferred_shape be shape or infer_shape_from_data with data as data
        Let total_elements be calculate_total_elements with shape as inferred_shape
        
        If length of flat_data is not equal to total_elements:
            Return ArrayResult with:
                success as false
                error_message as Some with value as "Data size " plus length of flat_data as String plus " does not match shape " plus total_elements as String
        
        Let strides_list be calculate_strides with shape as inferred_shape
        
        Let ndarray be NDArray with:
            data as flat_data
            shape as inferred_shape
            dtype as array_dtype
            ndim as length of inferred_shape
            size as total_elements
            strides as strides_list
        
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as true
            array as Some with value as ndarray
    
    Catch error:
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "Failed to create NDArray: " plus error as String

Process called "zeros" that takes 
    shape as List[Integer]
    and dtype as Optional[String]
    returns NDArray:

    Note: Create array filled with zeros
    Let array_dtype be dtype or "float64"
    Let total_size be calculate_total_elements with shape as shape
    
    Let zero_data be empty list
    For i from 0 to total_size minus 1:
        Add 0.0 to zero_data
    
    Let result be create_ndarray with data as zero_data and shape as Some with value as shape and dtype as Some with value as array_dtype
    Match result:
        When success as true and array as Some with value as ndarray:
            Return ndarray
        Default:
            Return NDArray with:
                data as zero_data
                shape as shape
                dtype as array_dtype
                ndim as length of shape
                size as total_size
                strides as calculate_strides with shape as shape

Process called "ones" that takes 
    shape as List[Integer]
    and dtype as Optional[String]
    returns NDArray:

    Note: Create array filled with ones
    Let array_dtype be dtype or "float64"
    Let total_size be calculate_total_elements with shape as shape
    
    Let ones_data be empty list
    For i from 0 to total_size minus 1:
        Add 1.0 to ones_data
    
    Let result be create_ndarray with data as ones_data and shape as Some with value as shape and dtype as Some with value as array_dtype
    Match result:
        When success as true and array as Some with value as ndarray:
            Return ndarray
        Default:
            Return NDArray with:
                data as ones_data
                shape as shape
                dtype as array_dtype
                ndim as length of shape
                size as total_size
                strides as calculate_strides with shape as shape

Process called "arange" that takes 
    start as Float
    and stop as Float
    and step as Optional[Float]
    returns NDArray:

    Note: Create evenly spaced values within a given interval
    Let step_size be step or 1.0
    Let values be empty list
    
    Let current_value be start
    While current_value is less than stop:
        Add current_value to values
        Set current_value to current_value plus step_size
    
    Let result be create_ndarray with 
        data as values 
        and shape as Some with value as list containing length of values 
        and dtype as Some with value as "float64"
    
    Match result:
        When success as true and array as Some with value as ndarray:
            Return ndarray
        Default:
            Return zeros with shape as list containing length of values and dtype as Some with value as "float64"

Process called "linspace" that takes 
    start as Float
    and stop as Float
    and num as Integer
    returns NDArray:

    Note: Create linearly spaced values
    Let values be empty list
    
    If num is equal to 1:
        Add start to values
    Else:
        Let step_size be stop minus start divided by num minus 1 as Float
        
        For i from 0 to num minus 1:
            Let value be start plus i as Float multiplied by step_size
            Add value to values
    
    Let result be create_ndarray with 
        data as values 
        and shape as Some with value as list containing num 
        and dtype as Some with value as "float64"
    
    Match result:
        When success as true and array as Some with value as ndarray:
            Return ndarray
        Default:
            Return zeros with shape as list containing num and dtype as Some with value as "float64"

Process called "reshape" that takes 
    array as NDArray
    and new_shape as List[Integer]
    returns ArrayResult:

    Note: Reshape array to new dimensions
    Try:
        Let new_total_elements be calculate_total_elements with shape as new_shape
        
        If new_total_elements is not equal to array.size:
            Return ArrayResult with:
                success as false
                error_message as Some with value as "Cannot reshape array of size " plus array.size as String plus " into shape with " plus new_total_elements as String plus " elements"
        
        Let new_strides be calculate_strides with shape as new_shape
        
        Let reshaped_array be NDArray with:
            data as array.data
            shape as new_shape
            dtype as array.dtype
            ndim as length of new_shape
            size as array.size
            strides as new_strides
        
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as true
            array as Some with value as reshaped_array
    
    Catch error:
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "Reshape failed: " plus error as String

Note: =============================================================================
Note: LINEAR ALGEBRA - Advanced Matrix Operations
Note: =============================================================================

Process called "dot" that takes 
    array1 as NDArray
    and array2 as NDArray
    returns ArrayResult:

    Note: Compute dot product of two arrays
    Try:
        Note: Handle 1D dot product
        If array1.ndim is equal to 1 and array2.ndim is equal to 1:
            If array1.shape[0] is not equal to array2.shape[0]:
                Return ArrayResult with:
                    success as false
                    error_message as Some with value as "Arrays must have same length for dot product"
            
            Let dot_product be 0.0
            For i from 0 to array1.shape[0] minus 1:
                Set dot_product to dot_product plus array1.data[i] as Float multiplied by array2.data[i] as Float
            
            Let result_array be create_ndarray with 
                data as list containing dot_product 
                and shape as Some with value as empty list 
                and dtype as Some with value as "float64"
            
            Return result_array
        
        Note: Handle 2D matrix multiplication
        If array1.ndim is equal to 2 and array2.ndim is equal to 2:
            Let m be array1.shape[0]
            Let n be array1.shape[1]
            Let p be array2.shape[1]
            
            If n is not equal to array2.shape[0]:
                Return ArrayResult with:
                    success as false
                    error_message as Some with value as "Matrix dimensions do not match for multiplication"
            
            Let result_data be empty list
            
            For i from 0 to m minus 1:
                For j from 0 to p minus 1:
                    Let sum be 0.0
                    For k from 0 to n minus 1:
                        Let a_index be i multiplied by n plus k
                        Let b_index be k multiplied by p plus j
                        Set sum to sum plus array1.data[a_index] as Float multiplied by array2.data[b_index] as Float
                    Add sum to result_data
            
            Let result_array be create_ndarray with 
                data as result_data 
                and shape as Some with value as list containing m, p 
                and dtype as Some with value as "float64"
            
            Return result_array
        
        Note: Handle matrix-vector multiplication
        If array1.ndim is equal to 2 and array2.ndim is equal to 1:
            Let m be array1.shape[0]
            Let n be array1.shape[1]
            
            If n is not equal to array2.shape[0]:
                Return ArrayResult with:
                    success as false
                    error_message as Some with value as "Matrix and vector dimensions do not match"
            
            Let result_data be empty list
            
            For i from 0 to m minus 1:
                Let sum be 0.0
                For j from 0 to n minus 1:
                    Let matrix_index be i multiplied by n plus j
                    Set sum to sum plus array1.data[matrix_index] as Float multiplied by array2.data[j] as Float
                Add sum to result_data
            
            Let result_array be create_ndarray with 
                data as result_data 
                and shape as Some with value as list containing m 
                and dtype as Some with value as "float64"
            
            Return result_array
        
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "Unsupported array dimensions for dot product"
    
    Catch error:
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "Dot product failed: " plus error as String

Process called "transpose" that takes array as NDArray returns ArrayResult:
    Note: Transpose array (reverse axes)
    Try:
        If array.ndim is equal to 1:
            Note: 1D array transpose returns copy
            Return ArrayResult with:
                success as true
                array as Some with value as array
        
        If array.ndim is equal to 2:
            Let m be array.shape[0]
            Let n be array.shape[1]
            Let transposed_data be empty list
            
            For j from 0 to n minus 1:
                For i from 0 to m minus 1:
                    Let original_index be i multiplied by n plus j
                    Add array.data[original_index] to transposed_data
            
            Let result_array be create_ndarray with 
                data as transposed_data 
                and shape as Some with value as list containing n, m 
                and dtype as Some with value as array.dtype
            
            Return result_array
        
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "Transpose not implemented for arrays with " plus array.ndim as String plus " dimensions"
    
    Catch error:
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "Transpose failed: " plus error as String

Process called "matrix_inverse" that takes matrix as NDArray returns ArrayResult:
    Note: Calculate matrix inverse using Gauss-Jordan elimination
    Try:
        If matrix.ndim is not equal to 2:
            Return ArrayResult with:
                success as false
                error_message as Some with value as "Matrix inverse requires 2D array"
        
        If matrix.shape[0] is not equal to matrix.shape[1]:
            Return ArrayResult with:
                success as false
                error_message as Some with value as "Matrix must be square for inversion"
        
        Let n be matrix.shape[0]
        
        Note: Create augmented matrix [A|I]
        Let augmented_data be empty list
        For i from 0 to n minus 1:
            For j from 0 to 2 multiplied by n minus 1:
                If j is less than n:
                    Let matrix_index be i multiplied by n plus j
                    Add matrix.data[matrix_index] to augmented_data
                Else:
                    Let identity_col be j minus n
                    If i is equal to identity_col:
                        Add 1.0 to augmented_data
                    Else:
                        Add 0.0 to augmented_data
        
        Note: Gauss-Jordan elimination
        For pivot from 0 to n minus 1:
            Note: Find pivot element
            Let pivot_row be pivot
            Let max_val be math.abs with value as augmented_data[pivot multiplied by 2 multiplied by n plus pivot] as Float
            
            For i from pivot plus 1 to n minus 1:
                Let current_val be math.abs with value as augmented_data[i multiplied by 2 multiplied by n plus pivot] as Float
                If current_val is greater than max_val:
                    Set max_val to current_val
                    Set pivot_row to i
            
            Note: Swap rows if needed
            If pivot_row is not equal to pivot:
                For j from 0 to 2 multiplied by n minus 1:
                    Let temp be augmented_data[pivot multiplied by 2 multiplied by n plus j]
                    Set augmented_data[pivot multiplied by 2 multiplied by n plus j] to augmented_data[pivot_row multiplied by 2 multiplied by n plus j]
                    Set augmented_data[pivot_row multiplied by 2 multiplied by n plus j] to temp
            
            Note: Scale pivot row
            Let pivot_val be augmented_data[pivot multiplied by 2 multiplied by n plus pivot] as Float
            If math.abs with value as pivot_val is less than 0.000001:
                Return ArrayResult with:
                    success as false
                    error_message as Some with value as "Matrix is singular (not invertible)"
            
            For j from 0 to 2 multiplied by n minus 1:
                Let index be pivot multiplied by 2 multiplied by n plus j
                Set augmented_data[index] to augmented_data[index] as Float divided by pivot_val
            
            Note: Eliminate column
            For i from 0 to n minus 1:
                If i is not equal to pivot:
                    Let factor be augmented_data[i multiplied by 2 multiplied by n plus pivot] as Float
                    For j from 0 to 2 multiplied by n minus 1:
                        Let target_index be i multiplied by 2 multiplied by n plus j
                        Let pivot_index be pivot multiplied by 2 multiplied by n plus j
                        Set augmented_data[target_index] to augmented_data[target_index] as Float minus factor multiplied by augmented_data[pivot_index] as Float
        
        Note: Extract inverse matrix from right half of augmented matrix
        Let inverse_data be empty list
        For i from 0 to n minus 1:
            For j from n to 2 multiplied by n minus 1:
                Let index be i multiplied by 2 multiplied by n plus j
                Add augmented_data[index] to inverse_data
        
        Let result_array be create_ndarray with 
            data as inverse_data 
            and shape as Some with value as list containing n, n 
            and dtype as Some with value as matrix.dtype
        
        Return result_array
    
    Catch error:
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "Matrix inversion failed: " plus error as String

Process called "eigenvalues" that takes matrix as NDArray returns ArrayResult:
    Note: Calculate eigenvalues using QR algorithm (simplified implementation)
    Try:
        If matrix.ndim is not equal to 2 or matrix.shape[0] is not equal to matrix.shape[1]:
            Return ArrayResult with:
                success as false
                error_message as Some with value as "Eigenvalues require square matrix"
        
        Let n be matrix.shape[0]
        Let A be copy_ndarray with array as matrix
        
        Note: Simplified QR algorithm (basic implementation)
        For iteration from 0 to 100 minus 1:
            Note: This would use proper QR decomposition in full implementation
            Let qr_result be qr_decomposition with matrix as A
            Match qr_result:
                When success as true and array as Some with value as decomp_result:
                    Set A to multiply_matrices with matrix1 as decomp_result and matrix2 as decomp_result
                Default:
                    Break
        
        Note: Extract diagonal elements as eigenvalues approximation
        Let eigenval_data be empty list
        For i from 0 to n minus 1:
            Let diag_index be i multiplied by n plus i
            Add A.data[diag_index] to eigenval_data
        
        Let result_array be create_ndarray with 
            data as eigenval_data 
            and shape as Some with value as list containing n 
            and dtype as Some with value as matrix.dtype
        
        Return result_array
    
    Catch error:
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "Eigenvalue calculation failed: " plus error as String

Note: =============================================================================
Note: FOURIER TRANSFORMS - Advanced Signal Processing
Note: =============================================================================

Type called "ComplexNumber":
    real as Float
    imaginary as Float

Process called "fft" that takes signal as NDArray returns ArrayResult:
    Note: Fast Fourier Transform implementation
    Try:
        If signal.ndim is not equal to 1:
            Return ArrayResult with:
                success as false
                error_message as Some with value as "FFT requires 1D signal"
        
        Let n be signal.shape[0]
        
        Note: Check if n is power of 2 (simplified requirement)
        If not is_power_of_two with value as n:
            Return ArrayResult with:
                success as false
                error_message as Some with value as "FFT requires signal length to be power of 2"
        
        Note: Convert real signal to complex
        Let complex_signal be empty list
        For i from 0 to n minus 1:
            Let complex_num be ComplexNumber with:
                real as signal.data[i] as Float
                imaginary as 0.0
            Add complex_num to complex_signal
        
        Note: Recursive FFT algorithm
        Let fft_result be fft_recursive with complex_data as complex_signal
        
        Note: Convert back to flat data for NDArray
        Let result_data be empty list
        For each complex_num in fft_result:
            Add complex_num.real to result_data
            Add complex_num.imaginary to result_data
        
        Let result_array be create_ndarray with 
            data as result_data 
            and shape as Some with value as list containing n, 2 
            and dtype as Some with value as "complex128"
        
        Return result_array
    
    Catch error:
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "FFT failed: " plus error as String

Process called "ifft" that takes spectrum as NDArray returns ArrayResult:
    Note: Inverse Fast Fourier Transform
    Try:
        If spectrum.ndim is not equal to 2 or spectrum.shape[1] is not equal to 2:
            Return ArrayResult with:
                success as false
                error_message as Some with value as "IFFT requires complex spectrum array"
        
        Let n be spectrum.shape[0]
        
        Note: Convert NDArray to complex numbers
        Let complex_spectrum be empty list
        For i from 0 to n minus 1:
            Let real_index be i multiplied by 2
            Let imag_index be i multiplied by 2 plus 1
            Let complex_num be ComplexNumber with:
                real as spectrum.data[real_index] as Float
                imaginary as spectrum.data[imag_index] as Float
            Add complex_num to complex_spectrum
        
        Note: Conjugate the spectrum
        Let conjugated_spectrum be empty list
        For each complex_num in complex_spectrum:
            Let conjugated be ComplexNumber with:
                real as complex_num.real
                imaginary as 0.0 minus complex_num.imaginary
            Add conjugated to conjugated_spectrum
        
        Note: Apply FFT to conjugated spectrum
        Let ifft_result be fft_recursive with complex_data as conjugated_spectrum
        
        Note: Conjugate and scale result
        Let final_result be empty list
        For each complex_num in ifft_result:
            Let scaled_real be complex_num.real divided by n as Float
            Let scaled_imag be 0.0 minus complex_num.imaginary divided by n as Float
            Add scaled_real to final_result
        
        Let result_array be create_ndarray with 
            data as final_result 
            and shape as Some with value as list containing n 
            and dtype as Some with value as "float64"
        
        Return result_array
    
    Catch error:
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "IFFT failed: " plus error as String

Process called "power_spectrum" that takes signal as NDArray returns ArrayResult:
    Note: Calculate power spectral density
    Try:
        Let fft_result be fft with signal as signal
        Match fft_result:
            When success as true and array as Some with value as spectrum:
                Let n be spectrum.shape[0]
                Let power_data be empty list
                
                For i from 0 to n minus 1:
                    Let real_part be spectrum.data[i multiplied by 2] as Float
                    Let imag_part be spectrum.data[i multiplied by 2 plus 1] as Float
                    Let magnitude_squared be real_part multiplied by real_part plus imag_part multiplied by imag_part
                    Add magnitude_squared to power_data
                
                Let result_array be create_ndarray with 
                    data as power_data 
                    and shape as Some with value as list containing n 
                    and dtype as Some with value as "float64"
                
                Return result_array
            
            Default:
                Return fft_result
    
    Catch error:
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "Power spectrum calculation failed: " plus error as String

Note: =============================================================================
Note: OPTIMIZATION ALGORITHMS - Advanced Mathematical Optimization
Note: =============================================================================

Type called "OptimizationResult":
    success as Boolean
    optimal_point as Optional[List[Float]]
    optimal_value as Optional[Float]
    iterations as Integer
    function_evaluations as Integer
    message as String

Process called "minimize_scalar" that takes 
    objective_function as String
    and bounds as Optional[List[Float]]
    and method as Optional[String]
    returns OptimizationResult:

    Note: Minimize scalar function using golden section search
    Try:
        Let optimization_method be method or "golden_section"
        Let search_bounds be bounds or list containing -10.0, 10.0
        
        Match optimization_method:
            When "golden_section":
                Let a be search_bounds[0]
                Let b be search_bounds[1]
                Let golden_ratio be 1.618033988749
                Let tolerance be 0.000001
                Let max_iterations be 1000
                
                Let c be b minus b minus a divided by golden_ratio
                Let d be a plus b minus a divided by golden_ratio
                
                Let fc be evaluate_objective_function with function_name as objective_function and x as c
                Let fd be evaluate_objective_function with function_name as objective_function and x as d
                
                Let iterations be 0
                Let function_evals be 2
                
                While math.abs with value as b minus a is greater than tolerance and iterations is less than max_iterations:
                    If fc is less than fd:
                        Set b to d
                        Set d to c
                        Set fd to fc
                        Set c to b minus b minus a divided by golden_ratio
                        Set fc to evaluate_objective_function with function_name as objective_function and x as c
                        Set function_evals to function_evals plus 1
                    Else:
                        Set a to c
                        Set c to d
                        Set fc to fd
                        Set d to a plus b minus a divided by golden_ratio
                        Set fd to evaluate_objective_function with function_name as objective_function and x as d
                        Set function_evals to function_evals plus 1
                    
                    Set iterations to iterations plus 1
                
                Let optimal_x be a plus b divided by 2.0
                Let optimal_f be evaluate_objective_function with function_name as objective_function and x as optimal_x
                
                Return OptimizationResult with:
                    success as true
                    optimal_point as Some with value as list containing optimal_x
                    optimal_value as Some with value as optimal_f
                    iterations as iterations
                    function_evaluations as function_evals plus 1
                    message as "Golden section search converged"
            
            Default:
                Return OptimizationResult with:
                    success as false
                    optimal_point as None
                    optimal_value as None
                    iterations as 0
                    function_evaluations as 0
                    message as "Unknown optimization method: " plus optimization_method
    
    Catch error:
        Return OptimizationResult with:
            success as false
            optimal_point as None
            optimal_value as None
            iterations as 0
            function_evaluations as 0
            message as "Optimization failed: " plus error as String

Process called "minimize_multivariable" that takes 
    objective_function as String
    and initial_point as List[Float]
    and method as Optional[String]
    returns OptimizationResult:

    Note: Minimize multivariable function using gradient descent
    Try:
        Let optimization_method be method or "gradient_descent"
        Let learning_rate be 0.01
        Let tolerance be 0.000001
        Let max_iterations be 10000
        
        Match optimization_method:
            When "gradient_descent":
                Let current_point be copy_list with list as initial_point
                Let iterations be 0
                Let function_evals be 0
                
                While iterations is less than max_iterations:
                    Note: Calculate gradient numerically
                    Let gradient be calculate_numerical_gradient with 
                        function_name as objective_function 
                        and point as current_point
                    
                    Set function_evals to function_evals plus length of current_point multiplied by 2
                    
                    Note: Calculate gradient magnitude
                    Let gradient_magnitude be 0.0
                    For each grad_component in gradient:
                        Set gradient_magnitude to gradient_magnitude plus grad_component multiplied by grad_component
                    Set gradient_magnitude to math.sqrt with value as gradient_magnitude
                    
                    If gradient_magnitude is less than tolerance:
                        Break
                    
                    Note: Update point
                    For i from 0 to length of current_point minus 1:
                        Set current_point[i] to current_point[i] minus learning_rate multiplied by gradient[i]
                    
                    Set iterations to iterations plus 1
                
                Let final_value be evaluate_multivariable_function with 
                    function_name as objective_function 
                    and point as current_point
                Set function_evals to function_evals plus 1
                
                Return OptimizationResult with:
                    success as true
                    optimal_point as Some with value as current_point
                    optimal_value as Some with value as final_value
                    iterations as iterations
                    function_evaluations as function_evals
                    message as "Gradient descent converged"
            
            Default:
                Return OptimizationResult with:
                    success as false
                    optimal_point as None
                    optimal_value as None
                    iterations as 0
                    function_evaluations as 0
                    message as "Unknown multivariable optimization method: " plus optimization_method
    
    Catch error:
        Return OptimizationResult with:
            success as false
            optimal_point as None
            optimal_value as None
            iterations as 0
            function_evaluations as 0
            message as "Multivariable optimization failed: " plus error as String

Note: =============================================================================
Note: INTERPOLATION AND APPROXIMATION - Advanced Curve Fitting
Note: =============================================================================

Process called "linear_interpolation" that takes 
    x_data as NDArray
    and y_data as NDArray
    and x_new as NDArray
    returns ArrayResult:

    Note: Linear interpolation between data points
    Try:
        If x_data.shape[0] is not equal to y_data.shape[0]:
            Return ArrayResult with:
                success as false
                error_message as Some with value as "x_data and y_data must have same length"
        
        Let n_points be x_new.shape[0]
        Let interpolated_values be empty list
        
        For i from 0 to n_points minus 1:
            Let x_target be x_new.data[i] as Float
            Let y_interpolated be interpolate_linear_point with 
                x_data as x_data 
                and y_data as y_data 
                and x_target as x_target
            Add y_interpolated to interpolated_values
        
        Let result_array be create_ndarray with 
            data as interpolated_values 
            and shape as Some with value as list containing n_points 
            and dtype as Some with value as "float64"
        
        Return result_array
    
    Catch error:
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "Linear interpolation failed: " plus error as String

Process called "polynomial_fit" that takes 
    x_data as NDArray
    and y_data as NDArray
    and degree as Integer
    returns ArrayResult:

    Note: Fit polynomial of specified degree to data
    Try:
        Let n_points be x_data.shape[0]
        Let n_coeffs be degree plus 1
        
        Note: Create Vandermonde matrix
        Let vandermonde_data be empty list
        For i from 0 to n_points minus 1:
            For j from 0 to n_coeffs minus 1:
                Let x_val be x_data.data[i] as Float
                Let power_val be math.pow with base as x_val and exponent as j as Float
                Add power_val to vandermonde_data
        
        Let vandermonde_matrix be create_ndarray with 
            data as vandermonde_data 
            and shape as Some with value as list containing n_points, n_coeffs 
            and dtype as Some with value as "float64"
        
        Match vandermonde_matrix:
            When success as true and array as Some with value as V:
                Note: Solve normal equation: (V^T V) c = V^T y
                Let VT_result be transpose with array as V
                Match VT_result:
                    When success as true and array as Some with value as VT:
                        Let VTV_result be dot with array1 as VT and array2 as V
                        Let VTy_result be dot with array1 as VT and array2 as y_data
                        
                        Match VTV_result:
                            When success as true and array as Some with value as VTV:
                                Match VTy_result:
                                    When success as true and array as Some with value as VTy:
                                        Let inverse_result be matrix_inverse with matrix as VTV
                                        Match inverse_result:
                                            When success as true and array as Some with value as VTV_inv:
                                                Let coefficients_result be dot with array1 as VTV_inv and array2 as VTy
                                                Return coefficients_result
                                            
                                            Default:
                                                Return inverse_result
                                    
                                    Default:
                                        Return VTy_result
                            
                            Default:
                                Return VTV_result
                    
                    Default:
                        Return VT_result
            
            Default:
                Return vandermonde_matrix
    
    Catch error:
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "Polynomial fitting failed: " plus error as String

Note: =============================================================================
Note: STATISTICAL FUNCTIONS - Advanced Statistical Analysis
Note: =============================================================================

Process called "histogram" that takes 
    data as NDArray
    and bins as Optional[Integer]
    and range as Optional[List[Float]]
    returns Dictionary[String, Any]:

    Note: Calculate histogram of data
    Try:
        Let n_bins be bins or 10
        Let data_min be find_array_minimum with array as data
        Let data_max be find_array_maximum with array as data
        
        Let hist_range be range or list containing data_min, data_max
        Let bin_width be hist_range[1] minus hist_range[0] divided by n_bins as Float
        
        Let bin_counts be empty list
        Let bin_edges be empty list
        
        Note: Initialize bins
        For i from 0 to n_bins minus 1:
            Add 0 to bin_counts
        
        For i from 0 to n_bins plus 1 minus 1:
            Let edge be hist_range[0] plus i as Float multiplied by bin_width
            Add edge to bin_edges
        
        Note: Count data points in each bin
        For i from 0 to data.size minus 1:
            Let value be data.data[i] as Float
            
            If value is greater than or equal to hist_range[0] and value is less than or equal to hist_range[1]:
                Let bin_index be math.floor with value as value minus hist_range[0] divided by bin_width
                Set bin_index to math.min with value1 as bin_index as Float and value2 as n_bins minus 1 as Float as Integer
                Set bin_counts[bin_index] to bin_counts[bin_index] plus 1
        
        Return Dictionary with:
            "counts" as bin_counts
            "bin_edges" as bin_edges
            "bin_width" as bin_width
    
    Catch error:
        Return Dictionary with:
            "error" as "Histogram calculation failed: " plus error as String

Process called "percentile" that takes 
    data as NDArray
    and percentiles as List[Float]
    returns ArrayResult:

    Note: Calculate percentiles of data
    Try:
        Let sorted_data be sort_array with array as data
        Let n be sorted_data.size
        Let result_values be empty list
        
        For each p in percentiles:
            If p is less than 0.0 or p is greater than 100.0:
                Add 0.0 to result_values  Note: Invalid percentile
                Continue
            
            Let index be p divided by 100.0 multiplied by n minus 1 as Float
            Let lower_index be math.floor with value as index as Integer
            Let upper_index be math.ceil with value as index as Integer
            
            If lower_index is equal to upper_index:
                Add sorted_data.data[lower_index] to result_values
            Else:
                Let fraction be index minus lower_index as Float
                Let lower_value be sorted_data.data[lower_index] as Float
                Let upper_value be sorted_data.data[upper_index] as Float
                Let interpolated_value be lower_value plus fraction multiplied by upper_value minus lower_value
                Add interpolated_value to result_values
        
        Let result_array be create_ndarray with 
            data as result_values 
            and shape as Some with value as list containing length of percentiles 
            and dtype as Some with value as "float64"
        
        Return result_array
    
    Catch error:
        Return ArrayResult with:
            success as false
            error_message as Some with value as "Percentile calculation failed: " plus error as String

Note: =============================================================================
Note: HELPER FUNCTIONS - Internal Implementation Support
Note: =============================================================================

Process called "flatten_nested_list" that takes list as List[Any] returns List[Any]:
    Note: Flatten nested list structure
    Let flattened be empty list
    
    For each item in list:
        If item is List:
            Let sub_flattened be flatten_nested_list with list as item as List[Any]
            For each sub_item in sub_flattened:
                Add sub_item to flattened
        Else:
            Add item to flattened
    
    Return flattened

Process called "infer_shape_from_data" that takes data as List[Any] returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Infer array shape from nested list structure
    If length of data is equal to 0:
        Return empty list
    
    Let shape be list containing length of data
    
    If data[0] is List:
        Let sub_shape be infer_shape_from_data with data as data[0] as List[Any]
        For each dim in sub_shape:
            Add dim to shape
    
    Return shape

Process called "calculate_total_elements" that takes shape as List[Integer] returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate total number of elements from shape
    Let total be 1
    For each dim in shape:
        Set total to total multiplied by dim
    Return total

Process called "calculate_strides" that takes shape as List[Integer] returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Calculate strides for array indexing
    Let strides be empty list
    Let current_stride be 1
    
    For i from length of shape minus 1 down to 0:
        Add current_stride to beginning of strides
        Set current_stride to current_stride multiplied by shape[i]
    
    Return strides

Process called "is_power_of_two" that takes value as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if value is power of 2
    If value is less than or equal to 0:
        Return false
    
    Return value bitwise_and value minus 1 is equal to 0

Process called "fft_recursive" that takes complex_data as List[ComplexNumber] returns List[ComplexNumber]:
    Note: Recursive FFT implementation (Cooley-Tukey algorithm)
    Let n be length of complex_data
    
    If n is equal to 1:
        Return complex_data
    
    Note: Divide
    Let even_data be empty list
    Let odd_data be empty list
    
    For i from 0 to n minus 1:
        If i modulo 2 is equal to 0:
            Add complex_data[i] to even_data
        Else:
            Add complex_data[i] to odd_data
    
    Note: Conquer
    Let even_fft be fft_recursive with complex_data as even_data
    Let odd_fft be fft_recursive with complex_data as odd_data
    
    Note: Combine
    Let result be empty list
    For k from 0 to n minus 1:
        Add ComplexNumber with real as 0.0 and imaginary as 0.0 to result
    
    For k from 0 to n divided by 2 minus 1:
        Let angle be -2.0 multiplied by 3.14159265359 multiplied by k as Float divided by n as Float
        Let twiddle be ComplexNumber with:
            real as math.cos with angle as angle
            imaginary as math.sin with angle as angle
        
        Let t be complex_multiply with z1 as twiddle and z2 as odd_fft[k]
        
        Set result[k] to complex_add with z1 as even_fft[k] and z2 as t
        Set result[k plus n divided by 2] to complex_subtract with z1 as even_fft[k] and z2 as t
    
    Return result

Process called "complex_multiply" that takes z1 as ComplexNumber and z2 as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Note: Multiply two complex numbers
    Return ComplexNumber with:
        real as z1.real multiplied by z2.real minus z1.imaginary multiplied by z2.imaginary
        imaginary as z1.real multiplied by z2.imaginary plus z1.imaginary multiplied by z2.real

Process called "complex_add" that takes z1 as ComplexNumber and z2 as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Note: Add two complex numbers
    Return ComplexNumber with:
        real as z1.real plus z2.real
        imaginary as z1.imaginary plus z2.imaginary

Process called "complex_subtract" that takes z1 as ComplexNumber and z2 as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Note: Subtract two complex numbers
    Return ComplexNumber with:
        real as z1.real minus z2.real
        imaginary as z1.imaginary minus z2.imaginary

Process called "copy_ndarray" that takes array as NDArray returns NDArray:
    Note: Create a copy of NDArray
    Return NDArray with:
        data as copy_list with list as array.data
        shape as copy_list with list as array.shape
        dtype as array.dtype
        ndim as array.ndim
        size as array.size
        strides as copy_list with list as array.strides

Process called "find_array_minimum" that takes array as NDArray returns Float:
    Note: Find minimum value in array
    If array.size is equal to 0:
        Return 0.0
    
    Let min_val be array.data[0] as Float
    For i from 1 to array.size minus 1:
        Let current_val be array.data[i] as Float
        If current_val is less than min_val:
            Set min_val to current_val
    
    Return min_val

Process called "find_array_maximum" that takes array as NDArray returns Float:
    Note: Find maximum value in array
    If array.size is equal to 0:
        Return 0.0
    
    Let max_val be array.data[0] as Float
    For i from 1 to array.size minus 1:
        Let current_val be array.data[i] as Float
        If current_val is greater than max_val:
            Set max_val to current_val
    
    Return max_val

Process called "sort_array" that takes array as NDArray returns NDArray:
    Note: Sort array in ascending order
    Let sorted_data be copy_list with list as array.data
    
    Note: Simple bubble sort (would use more efficient algorithm in production)
    Let n be length of sorted_data
    For i from 0 to n minus 2:
        For j from 0 to n minus i minus 2:
            If sorted_data[j] as Float is greater than sorted_data[j plus 1] as Float:
                Let temp be sorted_data[j]
                Set sorted_data[j] to sorted_data[j plus 1]
                Set sorted_data[j plus 1] to temp
    
    Let result_array be create_ndarray with 
        data as sorted_data 
        and shape as Some with value as array.shape 
        and dtype as Some with value as array.dtype
    
    Match result_array:
        When success as true and array as Some with value as sorted_array:
            Return sorted_array
        Default:
            Return array

Process called "copy_list" that takes list as List[Any] returns List[Any]:
    Note: Create a copy of the list
    Let copied_list be empty list
    For each item in list:
        Add item to copied_list
    Return copied_list